## 3. ABC Analysis

### Highest-Impact Products

| Product         | Spend        | Cumulative Share | Class |
| --------------- | ------------ | ---------------- | ----- |
| Epson Projector | R$ 1,041,600 | 30.0%            | A     |
| Dell Notebook   | R$ 766,500   | 52.2%            | A     |
| Office Desk     | R$ 406,800   | 63.9%            | A     |
| Steel Cabinet   | R$ 232,200   | 70.6%            | A     |
| 24" Monitor     | R$ 187,200   | 76.0%            | A     |

### Key Insight

Only five products account for more than 76% of total procurement spending.

Epson Projectors and Dell Notebooks alone represent over half of the annual procurement budget.

### Recommendations

* Require formal quotation processes for all Class A items.
* Establish annual pricing agreements for strategic products.
* Monitor market price fluctuations for high-impact products.

---

## 4. Procurement Seasonality

### Highest Spending Months

| Month     | Spend      |
| --------- | ---------- |
| September | R$ 655,109 |
| December  | R$ 444,335 |
| May       | R$ 415,959 |

### Key Insight

September and December represent significant procurement peaks, coinciding with academic-cycle milestones and end-of-year investments.

Furniture and Audiovisual Equipment also present the longest lead times, increasing the risk of delayed deliveries during peak periods.

### Recommendations

* Place high lead-time orders earlier in the procurement cycle.
* Reserve budget capacity for recurring seasonal peaks.
* Monitor supplier capacity ahead of high-demand periods.

---

## 5. Delay Distribution by Semester

| Semester     | Delay Rate |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| H1 (Jan–Jun) | 22.6%      |
| H2 (Jul–Dec) | 23.4%      |

### Key Insight

Delay rates remain consistent throughout the year.

The issue is structural rather than seasonal, suggesting that supplier performance—not procurement timing—is the primary cause of delivery delays.

### Recommendation

Focus improvement efforts on supplier management, SLA governance, supplier diversification, and continuous performance monitoring.

